# the kernel 
    - Process scheduler — decides which process runs on which CPU and when.
    - Memory management — allocates RAM, handles virtual memory and paging.
    - Filesystem drivers — ext4, XFS, Btrfs; the code that reads/writes disk.
    - Network stack — TCP/IP, routing, iptables/netfilter (the same netfilter your iptables-k8s-node.sh script configures).
    - Device drivers — talk to hardware: disks, network cards, GPUs.
    - System call interface — the entry point userspace uses to ask the kernel for things (read, write, open, fork).
    - Namespaces & cgroups — the isolation and resource-limiting features that make containers possible.

# the userspace 
    - Shell — bash, sh, zsh.
    - Core utilities — ls, cp, cat, grep, ps (e.g. GNU coreutils, or BusyBox in Alpine).
    - System libraries — glibc or musl, OpenSSL; the shared libraries apps link against.
    - Package managers — apt, apk, yum.
    - Runtimes & interpreters — Python, Node.js, the JVM, the Go runtime built into your demo-app binary.
    - Your application — the actual service you wrote.
    - Daemons/services — nginx, PostgreSQL, sshd.

